Global Political Systems

This visualization categorizes countries into four regime types: Liberal Democracy, Electoral Democracy, Electoral Autocracy, and Closed Autocracy. The data reveals a polarized world where some regions strengthen democratic institutions while others experience democratic backsliding and autocratic consolidation. This map captures the current state of global governance and the ongoing struggle between democracy and authoritarianism.

Global Democratic Trends

The world has recently become less democratic. Democracy is in decline across multiple metrics, whether we look at changes in the number of democracies, democratic rights, or countries experiencing autocratization.

87

Countries classified as democracies

35

Countries experiencing autocratization

15

Countries democratizing

5.7B

People living in autocratizing countries

Democracy and Autocracy Around the World

Africa

Journal of Democracy

Africa presents a mixed landscape where democratic progress coexists with persistent authoritarianism. While some countries have held peaceful elections and seen increased civic participation, others continue to experience military coups and restricted press freedom.

Asia

Progressive International

Asia is home to both vibrant democracies and entrenched autocracies. Democratic nations face growing pressure from nationalism and digital surveillance, while authoritarian regimes tighten control over political dissent and civil liberties.

Europe

International IDEA

Europe remains largely democratic, but recent years have seen challenges from rising populism, democratic backsliding, and weakened checks and balances in some countries. Still, strong institutions and active civil societies continue to uphold democratic norms across much of the continent.

North America

Progressive International

North America features well-established democracies, yet recent events have exposed deep political polarization and institutional stress. Democratic resilience remains strong, but issues such as misinformation, electoral integrity, and systemic inequality pose ongoing challenges.

South America

International IDEA

South America has experienced cycles of democratic renewal and authoritarian regression. While many countries have made strides toward greater transparency and civil participation, political instability and corruption continue to test the strength of democratic institutions.

Oceania

Journal of Democracy

Oceania has seen a mix of democratic governance and authoritarian tendencies. While some nations uphold democratic values and practices, others grapple with challenges such as political instability and the influence of external powers.
